									<comment username="srand" rating="8" value="Extremely clever game based on Chinese Whispers/Telephone for exactly 4 players. There are 64 cases, each of which includes a mission briefing, one piece of information for each player, and three questions to be asked at the end. Players pass their information to each other in specified interactions, e.g. player 1 listening first to the information from the player to their left, then passing both bits of information to the one on their right, then going back to the left for more. Each player listens to one other and speaks to one other, so some information is heard third-hand.

I&#039;ve played 6 of the cases at various different difficulty levels and the quality varies. Generally (but not always) they require memorizing the components of a logic puzzle, e.g. one includes five Yakuza each with a different occupation and a different missing finger; the better ones disguise this with other puzzles.

What&#039;s hard and occasionally frustrating is that a single weak link can break the puzzle for everyone - a missing word, transposed symbols and so on. In theory there&#039;s a scoring system where each player independently answers the questions and the score out of 12 determines how well the team has done, but our experience has been that errors are more likely to occur in the communication than the solving, which can leave no-one with correct answers.

Just delightful." />
