									<comment username="shadow_bind" rating="8" value="A terribly inefficient method of solving crimes, but a fantastic cerebral filler when you have exactly four people. Witness is at its peak when the cases contain potential red herrings or peculiar details which keep teams on their toes. Nothing beats having the rug pulled from under your collective feet when your team realises that a weird smudge in the clues was crucial to the case all along. 

However, a number of cases are straightforward and revolve around memorising a series of logical statements. It’s quite disappointing to encounter this sort of cases in the upper levels because they just require increasingly elaborate mnemonics. Also, the English translation contains a few vaguely-worded clues and typos which will affect the outcome of a case. (In particular, look out for cases #53 and #54.)

Uneven case qualities aside, this is a very unique title for the collection. Obviously the memory and simple puzzle-solving elements will not go down well with many, but I&#039;ve been fortunate so far to have had several accomplices (willing or otherwise) to help me complete a quarter of the cases." />
